Lebanon's comprehensive crisis
Beirut –– Looking back, a financial crisis usually seems to have warning signs before it happens; however, they rarely clearly indicate the direction of history.
Lebanon is in a similarly precarious situation, brought to a state of high instability by a predictable crisis.
Since the end of the Lebanese civil war (1975-1990), its economic and political system has been supported by foreign loans, a situation that inevitably led to a sustained increase in public debt.
At a certain node, external capital inflow had to stop. This node arrived at the end of 2019, and a series of negative shocks followed.
The sudden stop of this type of capital brought a severe triple crisis to the country.
The first question is the balance of international payments.
Lebanon's current-account deficit stood at 25% of its GDP, with a small export base, making it unable to pay for essential import goods.
The second question is finance.
Lebanon's public debt now totals more than 150% of its GDP.
Government revenue is collapsing under the weight of economic recession, the budget deficit has become very large, reaching 10% of GDP in 2019 and is still rapidly expanding.
What's most important is that Lebanon is also experiencing a banking crisis.
The main banks, as the main recipients of foreign capital inflows, have invested heavily in Lebanese sovereign debt (averaging 50% of their investment portfolios), and are now almost bankrupt.
These crises collectively pushed Lebanon's economy into the abyss.
Companies that were eager to borrow and import have started laying off employees or closing altogether.
An economic recession may lead to a Lebanese Great Depression.
The main capital source supporting Lebanon's fragile political economy is not oil, but remittances from expatriates, who are drawn in by high interest rates and a pegged exchange rate with the US dollar.
So it's not surprising to see signs of the "Dutch disease" everywhere: deposits have grown to more than 400% of GDP, creating a wealth effect and lowering the national savings rate to an unlikely level of 3% of GDP.
The degree of inequality is quite high, and it's still on the rise.
From 2000 to 2015, the effective exchange rate appreciated by about 50% after adjusting for inflation, greatly weakening the tradable sector.
Due to a lack of exportable goods and services, Lebanon has been losing educated young people.
But more importantly, large-scale capital inflows allowed the sect elite to solidify their position through sponsorship rather than performance.
These elites have extracted wealth from both the public and private sectors, establishing a bloated crony ruling clique.
Although this ensured political stability in the originally chaotic region, it failed to meet basic needs.
Even power supply was intermittent and unreliable, and the more fundamental challenges facing the macro economy remained unresolved.
The financial crisis triggered a political uprising.
A popular revolutionary movement has taken to the streets, opposing sectarianism, and demanding an end to corruption.
Despite this, the country's ruling power has consistently tilted its response to Lebanon's economic problems decisively in favor of the elite, indicating that the crisis may ultimately be resolved with the support of the poor and middle classes, further entrenching sectarian politics.
For example, the country refused to introduce capital controls, allowing each bank's main shareholders, including politicians in power, to decide how much cash to withdraw.
In reality, this enables the elite to transfer capital overseas, while ordinary citizens struggle to save.
In addition, the central bank lowered the deposit interest rate, but has not lowered the public debt interest rate, thereby increasing bank profits.
Despite international reserves continuing to decline, Lebanon still continues to repay its main foreign debt owed to domestic banks.
There are signs that it may start selling off state assets to elite-connected entities at fire-sale prices.
At the same time, the official exchange rate remained unchanged, while the elite were allowed to secure low exchange-rate US dollars, and ordinary citizens faced the reality of free-market exchange rates plummeting sharply.
When a country starts printing lira to pay public servants' salaries, devaluation will accelerate.
In reality, the central bank has already begun paying interest on dollars in lira, which accounts for more than 80% of all deposits, thereby creating the conditions to eliminate public debt through inflation.
As the debt reduction costs are pushed onto depositors through the "liraization" of depositor ownership, bank equity is largely spared.
If this scenario becomes a reality, Lebanon's middle class will be significantly reduced due to the decrease in actual wages and pensions, as well as the liquidation of savings.
The immigration process of educated young people will accelerate, even causing damage to the economic interests —— upon which the very system relies.
If the clerical system is to survive under these conditions, it will be a system of poverty-stricken people under its control, and this system of people can be controlled by increasingly cheaper shelters.
Ultimately, Lebanon will find itself in a similar situation to Venezuela.
Compared to that, the establishment of a new republic driven by revolutionaries would be carried out in a completely different way.
The revolutionaries want to improve Lebanon, not abandon it.
They believe its performance falls far short of its potential, and performance, meritocratic management, and social justice should replace corruption, nepotism, and inequality.
They hope to establish a vibrant high-tech industry, make agriculture more sustainable in the environment, position the nation as a cultural hub, and create more collaborative effects with immigrant communities.
To achieve these objectives, the reform movement hopes to seek an orderly reduction of public debt, which will be guaranteed by bank capital and the compulsory reduction of deposits of more than 50% of depositors.
They support moderate currency devaluation and a comprehensive improvement in the business environment to improve export competitiveness.
They will seek a deep fiscal restructuring, emphasizing the elimination of corrupt practices, and increasing spending on social projects and infrastructure.
Under the support of the international community, including the International Monetary Fund (IMF), the inevitable recession will be alleviated.
The current infighting over the composition of Lebanon's next cabinet is a part of a larger struggle in the process of finding a new political solution for the country.
The financial crisis poses a mortal threat to this country; but it also represents an opportunity for political change.
Lebanon's future remains uncertain.
